---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import HeroScene from '../components/HeroScene.astro';
---

<Base active="home">
  <!-- ───────────────────────── hero ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="hero section">
    <div class="wrap hero__grid">
      <div class="hero__copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">An experiment in building software</p>
        <h1>Software you can<br />watch grow.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          storytree is a small experiment with a big question at its centre: can software be
          built out in the open — by many people and AI&nbsp;agents at once, including people who've
          never written a line of code — and stay fair and trustworthy <em>because</em> of that
          openness, not in spite of it?
        </p>
        <div class="hero__cta">
          <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/how-it-works/">See how it works →</a>
          <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/constitution/">Read the constitution</a>
        </div>
        <p class="hero__note muted">
          Small on purpose. Invite-only for now — but the door to ask is wide open.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="hero__art">
        <HeroScene />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── the idea ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="lede">
        Picture a city you can watch being built — not from a press release months later,
        but live, brick by brick, with the reasoning behind every decision out where you can
        read it. That's the shape of storytree: a project grows as a living map of
        <strong>stories</strong>, and anyone can watch it happen.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── three pillars ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="grid grid--3">
        <article class="card pillar">
          <div class="pillar__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 40 40" width="40" height="40">
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="17" fill="var(--evergreen-soft)"/>
              <circle cx="13" cy="17" r="4.5" fill="#2f6b3f"/>
              <circle cx="27" cy="14" r="4.5" fill="#55a06a"/>
              <circle cx="22" cy="27" r="4.5" fill="#b06a24"/>
              <path d="M13 17 L27 14 M13 17 L22 27" stroke="#a98e5f" stroke-width="1.6"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Many builders, at once</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            People and AI&nbsp;agents work side by side, in parallel, fast. Software shouldn't be a
            black box a handful of people disappear into — it can be a shared, watchable space.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="card pillar">
          <div class="pillar__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 40 40" width="40" height="40">
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="17" fill="var(--evergreen-soft)"/>
              <path d="M12 20.5 l5 5 l11 -12" fill="none" stroke="#2f6b3f" stroke-width="3.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Nothing ships without proof</h3>
          <p class="muted" data-grounds="ADR-0020,ADR-0040">
            Ideas and concerns are raised in the open, discussed, and — once they pass real
            review gates — become working software. The gate isn't any one builder marking its own
            homework: whatever proves a piece works isn't what built it. Good intentions aren't
            enough; the work has to earn its place.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="card pillar">
          <div class="pillar__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 40 40" width="40" height="40">
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="17" fill="var(--evergreen-soft)"/>
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="9" fill="none" stroke="#2f6b3f" stroke-width="2.6"/>
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="2.6" fill="#b06a24"/>
              <path d="M20 4 V9 M20 31 V36 M4 20 H9 M31 20 H36" stroke="#2f6b3f" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>You don't have to trust us</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            The decisions, the reasoning, and the record are open and meant to be checked.
            We're building toward a way to simply <em>ask</em> the project, against its whole
            record — so a hidden agenda has nowhere left to hide.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── the bet ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap band">
      <div class="band__inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">The bet</p>
        <h2>An open record is a stronger foundation for trust than promises.</h2>
        <p class="lede">
          Most projects ask you to trust the people running them. We're trying to show you
          don't have to. A complete, open record you can interrogate directly can make a project
          genuinely fairer to everyone it touches — the people who use it, the people who build
          it, and the people affected by it. If that works, it's a way of building that more
          people can take part in. If it doesn't, you'll be able to see that too.
        </p>
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/how-it-works/">How the pieces fit together →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── front door ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose front">
      <p class="eyebrow">Where we are right now</p>
      <h2>Early, honest, and growing slowly.</h2>
      <p>
        storytree isn't open source yet — it's not ready to be. Taking part is invite-only while
        we iterate out the rough edges and build the guardrails real openness needs. Today one
        person still decides what gets built next — we're honest that "your voice counts" isn't
        yet "your vote counts." But this website is the open front door: you're welcome to watch,
        to ask hard questions, and to tell us where we're wrong — that last one especially.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__cta">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/contact/">Ask to come in</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/how-it-works/">Just looking? Start here</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .hero { padding-top: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 4.4rem); }
  .hero__grid { display: grid; gap: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 3rem); align-items: center; }
  @media (min-width: 860px) { .hero__grid { grid-template-columns: 1.05fr 1fr; } }
  .hero__copy h1 { margin-top: 0.2rem; }
  .hero__cta { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.7rem; margin-top: 1.6rem; }
  .hero__note { margin-top: 1.3rem; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  .hero em { font-style: italic; color: var(--ink); }

  .pillar { display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
  .pillar__icon { margin-bottom: 0.7rem; }
  .pillar h3 { margin-bottom: 0.35rem; }
  .pillar p { margin-bottom: 0; }

  .band {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #2f6b3f 0%, #245031 100%);
    border-radius: calc(var(--radius) + 4px);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow);
    overflow: hidden;
    position: relative;
  }
  .band::after {
    content: ""; position: absolute; inset: 0;
    background:
      radial-gradient(420px 300px at 92% -20%, rgba(169,200,127,0.30), transparent 60%),
      radial-gradient(360px 260px at 0% 120%, rgba(214,178,113,0.22), transparent 60%);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  .band__inner { position: relative; padding: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.4rem); max-width: 46rem; }
  .band .eyebrow { color: #f2cd92; }
  .band h2, .band .lede { color: #fdf6ec; }
  .band .lede { color: #e7ecdf; }
  .band h2 { margin-bottom: 0.7rem; }
  .band .btn--primary { background: #fffdfa; color: var(--evergreen-deep); margin-top: 0.4rem; }
  .band .btn--primary:hover { background: #fff; color: var(--evergreen-deep); }

  .front h2 { margin-top: 0.2rem; }
</style>
